"CORE_NARRATIVE: Light field depth estimation is fundamentally bottlenecked by the physical coupling of material and depth, which causes non-Lambertian reflections to corrupt Epipolar Plane Image (EPI) slope calculations. By replacing failing 2D-DFT frequency analysis with a three-layer angular signal decomposition and geometric angular features, we achieve physical signal decoupling to provide robust material priors that overcome low angular resolution limits.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by asserting that the persistent failure of EPI assumptions on non-Lambertian surfaces is rooted in the physical coupling of material and depth, severely limiting the upper bound and robustness of current depth estimation networks.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by demonstrating that current methods relying on 2D-DFT frequency analysis inherently fail at low angular resolutions (e.g., 9×9), proving that a paradigm shift toward physics-based geometric feature extraction is strictly necessary.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the three-layer angular signal decomposition as a direct physical model to decouple signals into ambient light, parallax, and material residuals, replacing invalid frequency features with geometric angular features. Explain how the GeometricDualMask architecture leverages these pixel-level material priors to route features and resolve EPI assumption conflicts between Lambertian and non-Lambertian regions.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the physical decoupling by highlighting the Random Forest classifier's 89.6% accuracy and the massive Cohen's d effect size (0.983) of the angular gradient feature, proving geometric features effectively separate materials at low resolutions. Furthermore, demonstrate that the domain-balanced dual-mask framework significantly improves depth estimation robustness across complex, mixed-domain scenes.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that physical signal decoupling via geometric modeling fundamentally resolves the non-Lambertian depth estimation bottleneck caused by low angular resolution limits. Echo the broader impact of replacing frequency features with reliable material priors to advance future unified light field 3D vision tasks."